
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lsmod` list-e module-haye kernel ra ke alan dare ejra mishe neshun mide. Yani, hameye driver-ha va barname-haye afzayeshi ke be kernel vasl shodan va daran kar mikonan.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 Hich gozine khas-i nadare ke kheili estefade beshe. `lsmod` sade tarin halatesh hame chio neshun mide.
    🔹 (Vali age bekhain output ro ba dastoor-haye dige pipe konin mesle `grep` baraye search, kheili karbordi mishe.)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lsmod

    🔹 List-e hameye module-haye kernel ro chap mikone. List kheili toolani mishe obdatan!

    $ lsmod | grep usb

    🔹 Faghat module-haee ke esmeshun `usb` dare ro neshun mide. In kheili rahat tare baraye peyda kardane module khass.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lsmod | less

    🔹 List-e module-ha ro chap mikone vali ba dastoor `less`, ke shoma mitunin safhe safhe bebinin va bala paeen konin. age list-e module-ha kheili toolani bashe, in kheili behtare.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lsmod` command lists the kernel modules that are currently loaded and running.  These are essentially drivers and other extensions that have been added to the kernel and are active.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹  `lsmod` typically doesn't require any options.  It shows all loaded modules in its simplest form.
    🔹  (However, piping its output to other commands like `grep` for searching is very common and useful.)

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lsmod

    🔹 Prints a list of all currently loaded kernel modules. The list can be quite long!

    $ lsmod | grep usb

    🔹 Shows only the modules that have `usb` in their name. This is a more targeted way to find a specific module.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lsmod | less

    🔹 Prints the list of modules but pipes the output to the `less` command, which allows you to scroll through the list page by page. This is very useful if the list of modules is long.
